AGI - From a search for computer scams to the discovery of ancient and important archaeological finds from Etruscan and Roman times. Protagonists of the discovery - in a villa of Nepi, municipality of Viterbese a short distance from Rome - were the carabinieri led by Lieutenant Felice Pasquali. Exposed above some beliefs of the house they were searching, the Army found archaeological findings that are suspected to be of illicit origin. The owner of the house, a 50-year-old Roman woman, has not been able to provide any explanation about it. And the carabinieri triggered the kidnapping and the complaint for violation of the code of cultural goods.
&nbsp;
The Soprintendenza for the province of Viterbo and the Southern Etruria then confirmed that the found goods are actually of archaeological interest. On the fact investigates the Viterbo Prosecution directed by Paolo Auriemma. The most probable hypothesis, according to investigators, is that the assets come from some clandestine excavation nearby. Among the pieces recovered there is also an amphora dated to the fifth century BC, considered important by experts for the rarity of the class of materials to which it belongs (very demanded in the illegal market of stolen archaeological goods). The goods seized by the carabinieri are: an envelope and a head in marble not relevant (busto dating III-IV sec. d.C., the head of the Julio-Claudia age); an Etruscan-corinzia cup with figurative decoration (half-sixth century a.C); a golden brocchetta with bands of probable vulcent origin (date V-IV sec. a.C); oinochoe to becco acroma, (date V-III century BC); 12 fragments of cerethan red dough pithos, dating first half VI century BC; 5 ceramic fragments of difficult attribution; a fragment of Etruscan ceramics corinzia dating VI century BC&nbsp;

